-- allium: 3
-- specs/kv-cache/per_stream_read_view_patching.allium
--
-- Scope: the per-stream patching obligation for the K/V *read*
-- views inside the attention path (llm_build_kqv). Companion to
-- specs/kv-cache/n_stream_layer.allium — the latter governs the
-- 4D layout, the per-stream allocator and the write-side CPY
-- patching that ships today; THIS spec governs the read-side
-- view patching that Tier 2 of PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md adds.
--
-- Why this spec exists: PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_4D N2.b extended
-- update_cache_copies (ik_llama.cpp/src/llama.cpp:630-749) to
-- recompute the WRITE-side CPY view offsets per stream every
-- decode. The READ views in llm_build_kqv
-- (ik_llama.cpp/src/llama-build-context.cpp:1663-1668 for K,
-- :1699-1704 for V on the flash-attn path) bake
-- `stream_id * k_cache->nb[3]` (resp. v_cache->nb[3]) at
-- graph-build time, where stream_id derives from kv.head /
-- kv_size_per_stream. Today the can_reuse_graph bailout at
-- src/llama.cpp:616 short-circuits reuse whenever
-- transformer_kv.n_stream > 1 precisely because that baked
-- offset is wrong for any decode whose stream differs from the
-- stream the graph was captured against. Tier 2's plan is to
-- extend update_cache_copies to walk a parallel registry of the
-- read-view nodes and rewrite their `data` pointer + ne[1]
-- in-place every decode, then drop the bailout. The contracts
-- below describe the post-Tier-2 state.
--
-- This spec is the binding RED test surface for Tier 2: every
-- contract here is currently UNSATISFIED on HEAD (the read
-- views are not in any registry; update_cache_copies does not
-- touch them; the bailout still fires at n_stream > 1). The
-- property test tests/spec/test-per-stream-read-view-patching.cpp
-- (P0.B.S4) will FAIL on HEAD and PASS when T2.b + T2.c land.
--
-- Source-of-truth confirmation (2026-05-21):
--   * The K read view is emitted by ggml_view_3d
--     (ik_llama.cpp/src/llama-build-context.cpp:1663-1668).
--     ggml_view_3d goes through ggml_view_impl which sets
--     result->op = GGML_OP_VIEW
--     (ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml.c:8539-8558, 8601-8615).
--     Confirmed: the K read view registers as GGML_OP_VIEW.
--   * The V read view (FA path) is emitted by ggml_view_3d
--     (ik_llama.cpp/src/llama-build-context.cpp:1699-1704). Same
--     ggml_view_impl path; also GGML_OP_VIEW.
--   * The downstream ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties
--     check at ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4687-4731
--     tolerates src_address and dst_address mismatch for
--     GGML_OP_VIEW and GGML_OP_CPY nodes (lines 4688-4691 and
--     4722-4730). Therefore the read views are PRE-SUPPORTED at
--     the backend layer; Tier 2 only adds the libllama-side
--     patching code.
--
-- Includes:
--   - External entities for the read-view registry and the
--     compute-graph node observable by the backend.
--   - Contracts for ReadViewStreamPatching (the shape obligation
--     on the patched views), ReadViewPatchedByUpdate (the
--     extension target inside update_cache_copies),
--     ReadViewIsLegitimateVIEW (the backend coupling),
--     PerStreamReadIsolation (the no-cross-stream-read
--     guarantee), MaskRespectsReadView (the mask <-> view
--     binding), and BugCAbsenceAtReadSide (the composition with
--     the write-side and dispatch-side closures).
--   - System-wide invariants lifting the contract clauses.
--   - Open questions for the points the implementation hasn't
--     committed to yet.
--
-- Excludes:
--   - The WRITE-side CPY patching. Owned by
--     specs/kv-cache/n_stream_layer.allium (PerStreamAllocator +
--     invariant clauses on update_cache_copies's existing
--     scope). THIS spec extends the same mechanism to the read
--     side; it does NOT re-state the write-side contracts.
--   - The backend's tolerance for VIEW src_address mismatch.
--     Owned by specs/graphs/cuda_graph_reuse.allium
--     (ViewCpyAddressTolerance contract). THIS spec asserts only
--     that the read views register as GGML_OP_VIEW; whether the
--     backend tolerates the per-call src_address change is a
--     separate property of that spec.
--   - The PerStreamDispatch contract (server-side batch split).
--     Owned by specs/scheduler/batch_composition.allium and
--     specs/kv-cache/n_stream_layer.allium. The read-view
--     patching described here applies under per-stream dispatch
--     (Tier 2 keeps that dispatch model); Tier 3's unified
--     dispatch is a separate spec.
--   - The can_reuse_graph bailout at src/llama.cpp:616 itself.
--     The bailout is the symptom Tier 2 removes. The contracts
--     here describe what must be TRUE for the removal to be
--     correct; the removal itself is a one-line edit covered by
--     PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md T2.e.

-- ============================================================
-- External entities — read-view registry objects
-- ============================================================

-- One entry in the parallel registry mirroring the existing
-- cache_copies[]. Holds the K or V read-view tensor handle
-- emitted by llm_build_kqv plus the metadata needed to recompute
-- its data pointer per decode. Storage shape mirrors the
-- existing `cache_copies` vector at
-- ik_llama.cpp/src/llama.cpp:759-761; Tier 2 introduces a
-- parallel `cache_attn_views[]` (or extends cache_copies) so the
-- patch loop can iterate it the same way it iterates cache_copies.
external entity ReadViewRegEntry {
    layer: Integer
    is_k: Boolean
    view: ReadViewTensor
    parent: KVTensor
    step: Integer
    stream_stride: Integer
}

-- One K or V read-view tensor as seen by the compute graph. The
-- tensor handle returned by ggml_view_3d at
-- ik_llama.cpp/src/llama-build-context.cpp:1663-1668 (K) and
-- :1699-1704 (V, FA path). Its `data` pointer encodes the
-- stream's offset; `ne[1]` is the per-tick effective context
-- length (n_kv). Both fields must be recomputed per decode under
-- Tier 2.
external entity ReadViewTensor {
    layer: Integer
    is_k: Boolean
    op: GgmlOp
    head_dim: Integer
    n_kv: Integer
    n_head_kv: Integer
    data_offset: Integer
}

-- The 4D K or V tensor for one transformer layer. Carries the
-- nb[3] stream stride the read view uses to compute its data
-- offset. Mirrors the KVTensor entity in n_stream_layer.allium;
-- redeclared here as external so this spec's contracts are
-- self-contained.
external entity KVTensor {
    layer: Integer
    head_dim: Integer
    kv_size_per_stream: Integer
    n_head_kv: Integer
    n_stream: Integer
    nb_3: Integer
}

-- The KQ_mask input tensor for one tick. Its row dimension
-- (n_kv) bounds the per-token attention window; under per-stream
-- dispatch the mask references only one stream's cells.
-- Production builder at ik_llama.cpp/src/llama.cpp:4545-4557
-- already computes _kv_mask_base = (head / kvps) * kvps to scope
-- the mask iteration to the current stream's cell range; Tier 2
-- ensures the read view's ne[1] matches that mask's n_kv.
external entity KQMask {
    n_kv: Integer
    n_tokens: Integer
    stream_id: Integer
}

-- One ggml_cgraph node observed by ggml-cuda's matching check.
-- Tier 2 must keep the read view's op = op_view so the
-- src_address tolerance carve-out in
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4687-4731 applies. Mirrors
-- the CgraphNode entity in cuda_graph_reuse.allium; redeclared
-- here as external for self-containment.
external entity CgraphNode {
    node_index: Integer
    op: GgmlOp
    src_address_0: Integer
    dst_address: Integer
}

-- One dispatched per-stream sub-batch in a tick. Carries the
-- stream_id, the n_kv value the mask was built against, and the
-- decoder's current head position. Mirrors the DispatchUnit
-- entity in n_stream_layer.allium; redeclared here so the
-- read-view contracts can quantify over per-tick state.
external entity DispatchUnit {
    stream_id: Integer
    n_kv: Integer
    head: Integer
    n_tokens: Integer
}

-- ============================================================
-- Enumerations
-- ============================================================

-- The ggml op kinds this spec quantifies over. Only the
-- VIEW-vs-other distinction is needed; the spec asserts that
-- read views register as op_view (so the backend's src_address
-- tolerance applies). op_other is the catch-all for every other
-- ggml op including the hypothetical PSKV variants that
-- llm_build_kqv emits downstream from the read views.
enum GgmlOp {
    op_view                                -- GGML_OP_VIEW
    op_cpy                                 -- GGML_OP_CPY
    op_flash_attn_ext_per_slot_kv          -- GGML_OP_FLASH_ATTN_EXT_PER_SLOT_KV
    op_other                               -- every other ggml op kind
}

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- The maximum streams supported. Mirrors max_streams in
    -- n_stream_layer.allium; pinned here so this spec's
    -- invariants can reference a numeric bound without
    -- cross-spec navigation.
    max_streams: Integer = 8

    -- The minimum cache-aware decode count after which Tier 2
    -- claims a steady-state recovery of the reuse path. The
    -- first decode per stream still capture-misses (one
    -- cudaGraphInstantiate per stream at warm-up); subsequent
    -- decodes for the same stream must hit the cache and route
    -- through cudaGraphExecUpdate. Used by the RED property
    -- test in tests/spec/test-per-stream-read-view-patching.cpp
    -- to gate the steady-state assertion.
    steady_state_decode_threshold: Integer = 2
}

-- ============================================================
-- Contracts
-- ============================================================

-- The ReadViewStreamPatching — the shape obligation on the
-- read-view tensor after the per-decode patch. Mirrors
-- PerStreamAllocator.CellsLocalToStream from
-- n_stream_layer.allium, lifted from cell indices to the read
-- view's tensor offset. Lives in the patched read view emitted
-- by llm_build_kqv at
-- ik_llama.cpp/src/llama-build-context.cpp:1663-1668 (K) and
-- :1699-1704 (V, FA path); the patch site is the Tier 2
-- extension of update_cache_copies at
-- ik_llama.cpp/src/llama.cpp:630 onward.
contract ReadViewStreamPatching {
    invoke: (entry: ReadViewRegEntry, unit: DispatchUnit) -> ReadViewTensor

    @invariant DataOffsetIsStreamLocal
        -- After the per-decode patch fires for DispatchUnit u
        -- on layer il (K or V), the read view's data_offset
        -- equals u.stream_id * parent.nb_3. The view's first
        -- byte therefore lies within
        -- [u.stream_id * parent.nb_3,
        --  (u.stream_id + 1) * parent.nb_3)
        -- inside the layer's K or V tensor. The formula mirrors
        -- the write-side patch at src/llama.cpp:662-672 (K)
        -- and :686-696 (V), specialised for the read view's
        -- whole-stream slice (cell 0 of the stream's slab; the
        -- read view always starts at the stream's base, not at
        -- the current head's cell).

    @invariant NeKvMatchesDispatchN
        -- After the patch, the read view's ne[1] equals
        -- unit.n_kv — the dispatch's effective context length.
        -- This binds the view's per-token axis to the mask's
        -- n_kv, so the attention path reads exactly
        -- unit.n_kv positions of the stream's slice. On HEAD
        -- the view's ne[1] is fixed at graph-build time to
        -- the n_kv of the captured tick; Tier 2 must rewrite
        -- it whenever the bucketed n_kv (transformer_kv.n,
        -- padded to 64 per src/llama.cpp:621) changes.

    @invariant NeAxesOtherThanPositionUnchanged
        -- ne[0] = head_dim and ne[2] = n_head_kv are determined
        -- by the layer's hparams and never change between
        -- decodes for a given layer. Tier 2's patch MUST leave
        -- ne[0] and ne[2] untouched; touching them would force
        -- a topology hash drift (ne is part of the matching
        -- check at ggml-cuda.cu:4713-4720) and defeat reuse.
        -- The patch is data-pointer + ne[1] only.

    @guidance
        -- Pending Tier 2: update_cache_copies extension does not
        -- yet touch the read views. The RED test in
        -- tests/spec/test-per-stream-read-view-patching.cpp
        -- will fail on HEAD: data_offset is whatever the
        -- graph-build-time stream_id produced, not the
        -- dispatch's current stream_id.
}

-- The ReadViewPatchedByUpdate — the obligation that
-- update_cache_copies (the Tier 2 extension target) rewrites
-- every active read view on every decode, in lockstep with the
-- existing write-side patching. Lives at the patch site
-- ik_llama.cpp/src/llama.cpp:630 onward; Tier 2 adds the parallel
-- iteration loop (T2.c in PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md).
contract ReadViewPatchedByUpdate {
    invoke: (cache: KVCache, unit: DispatchUnit) -> Set<ReadViewRegEntry>

    @invariant EveryActiveReadViewPatchedPerTick
        -- For every layer il with attention KV (the same gating
        -- the write-side patch already uses at
        -- src/llama.cpp:633-635 — `is_recurrent(il)` excluded),
        -- both the K read-view entry and the V read-view entry
        -- (when v_l is populated) are visited every tick. The
        -- patch rewrites the view's `data` pointer to
        -- parent->data + unit.stream_id * parent->nb[3] and
        -- rewrites ne[1] to unit.n_kv.

    @invariant PatchHappensBeforeBackendCompute
        -- update_cache_copies is invoked from can_reuse_graph
        -- at src/llama.cpp:625 (today, for the write side) BEFORE
        -- the cgraph is submitted to ggml_backend_cuda_graph_
        -- compute. Tier 2's extension MUST run in the same call,
        -- before any cudaGraphExecUpdate or cudaGraphLaunch
        -- fires for the tick. Patching after the launch would
        -- read stale offsets; patching only on miss would
        -- defeat reuse-with-patch (the read views' addresses
        -- would be wrong on a cached-graph hit).

    @invariant PatchIsIdempotentAtNStream1
        -- At transformer_kv.n_stream == 1, unit.stream_id is
        -- always 0 and the per-stream offset collapses to 0.
        -- The patch then writes the read view's `data` to
        -- parent->data + 0, which is parent->data — exactly
        -- what the legacy build emits. The Tier 2 extension is
        -- therefore a no-op at NP=1 (current production
        -- geometry); GP3.n in PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md gates
        -- byte-identity of MTP NP=1 output as the binding
        -- check.

    @invariant FailureReturnsFalseLikeWriteSide
        -- The existing update_cache_copies returns false when a
        -- captured cache_copies[] entry's invariants no longer
        -- hold (e.g., view_src tensor pointer changed; cf
        -- src/llama.cpp:654, :678, :704, :730). The Tier 2
        -- extension follows the same convention for the read
        -- side: if a registered read view's parent pointer or
        -- op kind diverges from capture, return false, which
        -- forces can_reuse_graph to miss (reason 10) and the
        -- backend falls through to a fresh capture. No silent
        -- corruption.

    @guidance
        -- Pending Tier 2: update_cache_copies extension. RED
        -- test in tests/spec/test-per-stream-read-view-patching.cpp
        -- will fail on HEAD because the read views are not in
        -- any registry yet (T2.b adds the registry; T2.c adds
        -- the patch loop).
}

-- The ReadViewIsLegitimateVIEW — the coupling between the
-- read-view nodes and the backend's src_address-tolerance carve-
-- out. The Tier 2 patch changes the read view's `data` pointer
-- every decode; the backend's matching check at
-- ik_llama.cpp/ggml/src/ggml-cuda.cu:4687-4731 tolerates that
-- mismatch ONLY for ops in {GGML_OP_VIEW, GGML_OP_CPY}. If a
-- future refactor were to replace ggml_view_3d in llm_build_kqv
-- with a different op (e.g., a hypothetical fused
-- GGML_OP_FLASH_ATTN_EXT_PER_SLOT_KV variant that takes the
-- stream-base internally), the cudaGraphExecUpdate path would
-- invalidate the cached graph on every decode and defeat the
-- perf recovery Tier 2 is supposed to enable.
contract ReadViewIsLegitimateVIEW {
    invoke: (entry: ReadViewRegEntry, node: CgraphNode) -> Boolean

    @invariant RegisteredReadViewsRegisterAsViewOp
        -- For every ReadViewRegEntry e, the cgraph node emitted
        -- for e.view in the per-tick graph has op = op_view.
        -- Confirmed against HEAD: llm_build_kqv calls
        -- ggml_view_3d (src/llama-build-context.cpp:1663-1668
        -- for K; :1699-1704 for V on the FA path);
        -- ggml_view_3d -> ggml_view_impl sets result->op =
        -- GGML_OP_VIEW (ggml/src/ggml.c:8539-8558, 8601-8615).
        -- The clause names the property a future refactor MUST
        -- preserve.

    @invariant SrcAddressMismatchToleratedAtBackend
        -- Because the registered read views have op = op_view,
        -- the per-tick src_address change introduced by the
        -- Tier 2 patch does NOT invalidate the matching check
        -- in ggml_graph_node_has_matching_properties at
        -- ggml-cuda.cu:4722-4730 (the per-src loop's early-
        -- return carves out VIEW and CPY ops). The cached
        -- cudaGraphExec is reused via the cudaGraphExecUpdate
        -- patch path, not the full reinstantiate path. This is
        -- the property that makes Tier 2's perf recovery
        -- tractable; without it, every stream change would
        -- force a reinstantiate per tick. Cross-references
        -- ViewCpyAddressTolerance.ViewCpySrcAddressMismatch-
        -- ToleratedOnVcpy in specs/graphs/cuda_graph_reuse.allium.

    @invariant NonViewReadPathInvalidatesReuse
        -- For any CgraphNode n with n.op != op_view AND n.op
        -- != op_cpy, a src_address mismatch DOES invalidate the
        -- match (ggml-cuda.cu:4722-4730). If a future fused
        -- attention op subsumes the read view and exposes the
        -- stream's data pointer as a `src` of that op, the
        -- patch site MUST be reworked to keep the cgraph node
        -- visible to the backend as op_view (e.g., emit a
        -- separate VIEW node feeding the fused op rather than
        -- collapsing them).

    @guidance
        -- The PSKV op (op_flash_attn_ext_per_slot_kv) at
        -- ik_llama.cpp/src/llama-build-context.cpp:1726 consumes
        -- the K and V read views as its src[1] and src[2]. The
        -- VIEWs themselves are separate cgraph nodes upstream
        -- of the PSKV op; this contract binds the upstream
        -- VIEWs, not the PSKV op. PSKV's own src[1] and src[2]
        -- src_address will mismatch capture every decode, but
        -- the PSKV op references the patched VIEW outputs by
        -- node pointer, so the data flow remains correct as
        -- long as the VIEWs themselves are patched.
}

-- The PerStreamReadIsolation — the no-cross-stream-read
-- property at the read-view level. Mirrors the write-side
-- NoCrossStreamLeakage invariant in n_stream_layer.allium,
-- lifted from "writes destined for stream s never mutate cells
-- in stream s'" to "reads bound for stream s only access cells
-- in stream s's slice".
contract PerStreamReadIsolation {
    invoke: (unit: DispatchUnit, view: ReadViewTensor) -> Boolean

    @invariant ReadByteRangeWithinStreamSlice
        -- For DispatchUnit u and its layer-il K (or V) read
        -- view v_view, the byte range
        --   [v_view.data_offset,
        --    v_view.data_offset + v_view.n_kv * parent.nb[1])
        -- is contained within
        --   [u.stream_id * parent.nb[3],
        --    (u.stream_id + 1) * parent.nb[3]).
        -- The kernel reading the view (PSKV or the legacy FA)
        -- therefore sees only stream u.stream_id's cells, even
        -- though the underlying K/V tensor is shared across all
        -- streams. Cross-references StreamPartition in
        -- n_stream_layer.allium.

    @invariant NoStreamBoundaryStrideOverflow
        -- The read view's per-position stride (parent->nb[1])
        -- multiplied by the view's n_kv MUST NOT exceed the
        -- stream's nb[3] budget. Equivalently:
        -- v_view.n_kv <= parent.kv_size_per_stream. The
        -- per-stream n_kv is bucketed to multiples of 64 by
        -- src/llama.cpp:621 and bounded above by
        -- kv_size_per_stream by the allocator; Tier 2 inherits
        -- the bound and asserts it at the read-view layer.

    @invariant SharedParentSafeUnderTier2Patching
        -- Even though the K and V tensors are SHARED across all
        -- streams (one ggml_tensor per layer, ne[3] = n_stream),
        -- the read view's stream-local data_offset guarantees
        -- that two dispatches for different streams read
        -- disjoint byte ranges. No locking or copy is needed;
        -- the n_stream layout's strict partition is the
        -- structural correctness argument.
}

-- The MaskRespectsReadView — the binding between the KQ mask
-- and the read view's bounded token range. The mask must
-- filter cells WITHIN the read view's stream slice; it must not
-- reference cells outside that slice. Mirrors MaskPerStream in
-- n_stream_layer.allium, specialised to the read view's actual
-- ne[1] (not the global cache.size).
contract MaskRespectsReadView {
    invoke: (unit: DispatchUnit, view: ReadViewTensor, mask: KQMask) -> Boolean

    @invariant MaskNKvEqualsViewNeKv
        -- For DispatchUnit u, the KQ mask's n_kv equals the
        -- read view's ne[1]. Both are set from
        -- transformer_kv.n (the bucketed effective context
        -- length). The mask builder at src/llama.cpp:4517-4561
        -- already iterates the per-stream cells range; Tier 2
        -- only adds the view-side bound.

    @invariant MaskCellIndexResolvesToStreamSlice
        -- For each (token_index j, mask_row i) the mask
        -- consults cells[_kv_mask_base + i] where
        -- _kv_mask_base = (head / kvps) * kvps
        -- (src/llama.cpp:4554-4557). That base equals
        -- u.stream_id * kvps, so the cell index resolves to
        -- the same stream slice the read view selects via
        -- data_offset. Mask and view see the same physical cell
        -- range by construction.

    @invariant MaskVisibilityBoundedByPositionAndSeqId
        -- The mask bit for (j, i) is visible (0 in F16/F32 form)
        -- iff cells[_kv_mask_base + i].has_seq_id(seq_id) AND
        -- cells[_kv_mask_base + i].pos <= batch.pos[j], else
        -- -infinity. Lifts the existing visibility rule at
        -- src/llama.cpp:4490-4493 (MTP-fused path) and the
        -- legacy noalibi paths at src/llama.cpp:4559 onward.

    @guidance
        -- Pending Tier 2: the read view's ne[1] is not yet
        -- patched per-decode, so the equality
        -- mask.n_kv = view.ne[1] is met today only because
        -- both are read from transformer_kv.n at graph-build
        -- time. Once Tier 2 makes ne[1] a per-decode quantity
        -- and the n_kv bucketing changes within a topology
        -- bucket, the contract binds the patch to also update
        -- ne[1] in lockstep with the mask's n_kv.
}

-- The BugCAbsenceAtReadSide — the composition argument: the
-- read-side per-stream isolation, the write-side per-stream
-- isolation (from n_stream_layer.allium), and the per-stream
-- dispatch (from batch_composition.allium) together make a
-- mixed-batch impossible at the KERNEL INPUT layer, not just
-- the scheduler layer. Tier 2 preserves this composition.
contract BugCAbsenceAtReadSide {
    invoke: (cache: KVCache) -> Boolean

    @invariant ReadSideMixedBatchImpossibleByConstruction
        -- Under PerStreamDispatch (n_stream_layer.allium) +
        -- ReadViewStreamPatching (this spec) + write-side
        -- update_cache_copies (n_stream_layer.allium), the K
        -- and V read-view inputs feeding mul_mat / FA carry
        -- bytes from exactly ONE stream's slice. Two streams'
        -- cells never appear in the same kernel-input tensor
        -- because (a) dispatch routes one stream's tokens per
        -- llama_decode and (b) the read view's data_offset
        -- selects exactly that stream's slice within the
        -- shared K/V tensor.

    @invariant WriteAndReadSideCompose
        -- The write-side patch at src/llama.cpp:662-672 (K) and
        -- :686-696 (V) writes a stream-local cell offset based
        -- on transformer_kv.head; the read-side patch (Tier 2)
        -- reads a stream-local base offset based on the same
        -- transformer_kv.head / kvps. Both formulas use the
        -- same divisor (kv_size_per_stream) and the same
        -- parent->nb[3] stride; they cannot disagree about which
        -- stream's slice the current decode owns. The Bug C
        -- closure load-bears on this agreement.

    @invariant PreservesNStream1Production
        -- At n_stream == 1 (current production), the stream_id
        -- divisor produces 0 always; both write and read
        -- patches collapse to the legacy single-stream
        -- behaviour. Bug C is trivially absent (only one stream
        -- exists). This is the property GP3.n in
        -- PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md binds via the MTP NP=1
        -- production smoke.

    @guidance
        -- This contract is what makes the dropping of the
        -- can_reuse_graph bailout at src/llama.cpp:616 safe.
        -- The bailout was a conservative cover for the gap THIS
        -- spec closes. Once Tier 2 lands, the bailout becomes
        -- dead code and is removed per
        -- PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md T2.e.
}

-- ============================================================
-- External entities — referenced by the contracts above
-- ============================================================

-- The whole KV cache. Mirrors KVCache in n_stream_layer.allium;
-- redeclared so the BugCAbsenceAtReadSide contract's signature
-- is self-contained without forcing a cross-spec import for the
-- type alone.
external entity KVCache {
    n_layer: Integer
    n_stream: Integer
    kv_size_per_stream: Integer
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants — system-wide
-- ============================================================

-- The read-view offset partition property. For every dispatched
-- (stream, layer, K-or-V) triple, the read view's data offset
-- equals stream_id * parent.nb[3]. Lifts
-- ReadViewStreamPatching.DataOffsetIsStreamLocal to a
-- system-wide property over all active dispatches per tick.
invariant ReadViewOffsetPartition {
    for entry in ReadViewRegEntries:
        for unit in DispatchUnits:
            ActiveAtTick(entry, unit)
                implies entry.view.data_offset = unit.stream_id * entry.parent.nb_3
}

-- The per-stream read-isolation property at the system level.
-- For every active read view in any tick, the byte range it
-- exposes to the kernel falls entirely within its stream's
-- slice. Cross-references StreamPartition in n_stream_layer.allium.
invariant ReadIsolationSystemWide {
    for entry in ReadViewRegEntries:
        for unit in DispatchUnits:
            ActiveAtTick(entry, unit)
                implies ReadByteRangeWithin(entry.view, unit.stream_id, entry.parent)
}

-- The op-kind preservation property. Every read view in the
-- registry MUST emit a cgraph node with op = op_view, so the
-- backend's src_address tolerance applies. A future refactor
-- that breaks this invariant silently defeats Tier 2's perf
-- recovery (it doesn't break correctness, but the cache thrash
-- shows up as a measurable regression).
invariant ReadViewOpKindPreserved {
    for entry in ReadViewRegEntries:
        for node in CgraphNodesFor(entry):
            node.op = op_view
}

-- The patch-before-launch property. The Tier 2 extension of
-- update_cache_copies MUST run before the cgraph is submitted
-- to the CUDA backend. Lifts
-- ReadViewPatchedByUpdate.PatchHappensBeforeBackendCompute to a
-- per-tick system property.
invariant PatchPrecedesBackendCompute {
    for unit in DispatchUnits:
        UpdateCacheCopiesInvokedAt(unit) < BackendComputeInvokedAt(unit)
}

-- The composition property. The system-wide absence of Bug C at
-- the kernel-input layer follows from (a) per-stream dispatch
-- (one stream per llama_decode), (b) write-side patching, and
-- (c) read-side patching (Tier 2). Each of the three is
-- independently necessary; together they are sufficient.
invariant BugCAbsenceCompositional {
    for unit in DispatchUnits:
        for entry in ReadViewRegEntries:
            ActiveAtTick(entry, unit)
                implies (DispatchUnitTokensShareSeqId(unit)
                         and WriteViewStreamLocal(unit)
                         and ReadViewStreamLocal(entry, unit))
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open Questions
-- ============================================================

-- OQ-1: registry shape. Tier 2 may extend the existing
--   cache_copies[] vector (storing read views alongside write
--   CPY nodes, distinguished by a flag) OR add a parallel
--   cache_attn_views[] vector. The first is mechanically smaller;
--   the second keeps the write-side patch loop unchanged.
--   PHASE_NSTREAM_KV_PERF.md T2.b is undecided. Either form
--   satisfies the contracts above. Resolve at T2.b
--   implementation time.
--
-- OQ-2: V read view on the non-FA path. The V read view at
--   src/llama-build-context.cpp:1758-1772 (the cparams.flash_attn
--   == false branch) uses a different shape and a 0 offset
--   (line 1764, 1770). Production runs with flash_attn = true
--   so this branch is cold; whether Tier 2 must also patch the
--   non-FA V view depends on whether any production geometry
--   exercises it. Resolve at T2.a probe: if any test in the
--   binding gate set (GP3.e DFlash suite, GP3.f r5-probe-c4)
--   exercises non-FA attention at n_stream > 1, extend the
--   patch; otherwise leave the non-FA branch alone with a
--   guarded GGML_ASSERT(kv.n_stream == 1) and add it to the
--   n_stream == 1 follow-up list (the same list that already
--   gates build_k_shift and build_defrag at n_stream == 1 per
--   PHASE_NSTREAM_KV closure follow-ups).
--
-- OQ-3: n_kv bucketing interaction. The bucketing at
--   src/llama.cpp:621 rounds n_kv to multiples of 64 so
--   consecutive draft steps within a 64-cell bucket share a
--   cached graph. Tier 2's ne[1] patch interacts with this:
--   ne[1] CHANGES whenever the bucketed n_kv crosses a 64-cell
--   boundary, forcing a topology miss (the matching check at
--   ggml-cuda.cu:4713-4716 compares ne). Verify at T2.f bench:
--   is the cross-bucket miss rate material? If yes, evaluate
--   whether the patch should pin ne[1] to the bucket's upper
--   bound and let the mask + per_row_k_bound enforce the
--   actual position bound (preferred per existing PSKV
--   plumbing). Tier 2 closure does not block on this; it's a
--   perf-tuning open question for the post-Tier-2 telemetry.
--
-- OQ-4: graph cache eviction under Tier 2. With the bailout
--   dropped, the per-stream graphs share a single topology hash
--   (the cgraph op-sequence is identical across streams; only
--   src_address differs). At n_stream <= max_streams = 8 and
--   GGML_CUDA_GRAPH_MAX = 128 (cuda_graph_reuse.allium config),
--   the cache holds all per-stream variants comfortably; no
--   eviction expected at production geometry. Verify at T2.f:
--   instrument ggml_cuda_get_graph (ggml-cuda.cu:4549-4576) to
--   count evictions over a 1000-decode steady-state run. If
--   evictions are non-zero, the cache is thrashing on a
--   different axis and needs separate analysis.

